          "identifier": "exists_isMIntegralCurveAt_of_contMDiffAt"
        },
        {
          "type": "TextualBody",
          "purpose": "classifying",
          "value": "partial"
        },
        {
          "type": "TextualBody",
          "purpose": "classifying",
          "value": "match_kind:special_case"
        },
        {
          "type": "TextualBody",
          "purpose": "tagging",
          "value": "proposition"
        },
        {
          "type": "TextualBody",
          "purpose": "describing",
          "value": "Mathlib formalizes LOCAL existence and uniqueness of integral curves of a `C^∞` vector field on a manifold (`exists_isMIntegralCurveAt_of_contMDiffAt`), but the global statement specific to compact manifolds — that every trajectory of a smooth vector field on a compact manifold exists for all time — was not located in Mathlib.",
          "format": "text/plain"
        }
      ],
      "target": {
        "source": "https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Picard%E2%80%93Lindel%C3%B6f_theorem?oldid=1346301030",
        "selector": {
          "type": "TextQuoteSelector",
          "exact": "Nevertheless, if f is"
        }
      }
    },
    {
      "id": "urn:wikilean:Picard-Lindelof_theorem:anno-17",
      "type": "Annotation",
      "motivation": "classifying",
      "created": "2026-05-27T18:35:34+00:00",
      "generator": {
        "type": "Software",
        "name": "WikiLean 2-agent annotation pipeline",
        "homepage": "https://github.com/Deicyde/WikiLean"
      },
      "body": [
        {
          "type": "TextualBody",
          "purpose": "classifying",
          "value": "not_formalized"
        },
        {
          "type": "TextualBody",
          "purpose": "tagging",
          "value": "example"
        },
        {
          "type": "TextualBody",
          "purpose": "describing",
          "value": "The IVP dy/dt = a·y^{2/3}, y(0)=0 admits two distinct solutions (y(t)=0 and y(t)=(at/3)^3), showing that the Lipschitz hypothesis of Picard–Lindelöf is necessary for uniqueness. Mathlib formalizes the positive direction (Picard–Lindelöf, ContractingWith etc.) but has no counter-examples for the failure case — this specific non-uniqueness instance has not been formalized.",
          "format": "text/plain"
        }
      ],
      "target": {
        "source": "https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Picard%E2%80%93Lindel%C3%B6f_theorem?oldid=1346301030",
        "selector": {
          "type": "TextQuoteSelector",
          "exact": "By contrast for an equation"
        }
      }
    }
